Title: Alice's Adventures in Wonderland
Credit: Screenplay adaptation of
Author: Lewis Carroll's novel (1865, public domain)
Draft date: 7/18/2026
Notes: Original fountain-format adaptation for parser testing purposes.

====

FADE IN:

EXT. RIVERBANK - AFTERNOON

Dappled sunlight through leaves. ALICE (7) sits beside her older SISTER, who reads silently, absorbed. Alice peers over, unimpressed -- no pictures, no conversations.

ALICE
(to herself)
What good is a book with no pictures or conversations?

A blur of white streaks past at the edge of the frame.

ALICE (CONT'D)
(sitting up)
Did you see that?

Her sister doesn't look up. Alice scrambles to her feet and follows.

EXT. HEDGE ROW - CONTINUOUS

The WHITE RABBIT, in a waistcoat, fishes a pocket watch from his pocket.

WHITE RABBIT
Oh dear! Oh dear! I shall be too late!

Alice rounds the hedge just as the Rabbit vanishes down a large hole.

ALICE
Wait -- please!

She kneels at the rabbit-hole's edge, peers in, and without a second thought, climbs down after it.

INT. RABBIT-HOLE - CONTINUOUS (FALLING)

A long, slow, impossible fall. Shelves of books and jars of marmalade drift past on the walls as Alice tumbles, entirely unhurried.

ALICE (V.O.)
(calm, curious)
Well, after such a fall as this, I shall think nothing of tumbling down stairs.

CUT TO:

INT. LONG HALL - CONTINUOUS

Alice lands, unharmed, in a hallway lined with locked doors. A tiny glass table holds a single golden key and a bottle labeled DRINK ME.

She tries the key on a door no bigger than a mousehole -- too small to fit through, but she can see a beautiful garden beyond it.

ALICE
(sighing)
How I wish I could shut up like a telescope.

She eyes the bottle, hesitates, then drinks.

Alice SHRINKS to ten inches tall.

ALICE (CONT'D)
(delighted, then alarmed)
Oh! Curiouser and curiouser --

She's left the key on the table, now impossibly high above her.

A small cake appears on the floor marked EAT ME. Alice eats it without hesitation.

She GROWS -- rapidly -- until her head presses the ceiling.

ALICE (CONT'D)
(muffled, cramped)
This is decidedly too much of a good thing.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

EXT. WONDERLAND GARDEN - DAY

Alice, restored to a reasonable size, wanders among oversized flowers. The CHESHIRE CAT lounges on a branch overhead, grinning.

CHESHIRE CAT
Where are you going?

ALICE
Which way ought I to go from here?

CHESHIRE CAT
That depends a good deal on where you want to get to.

ALICE
I don't much care where --

CHESHIRE CAT
Then it doesn't much matter which way you go.

Alice frowns, considering this. The Cat's body fades first, leaving only the grin.

ALICE
(startled)
I've seen a cat without a grin, but never a grin without a cat.

CHESHIRE CAT
(fading further)
You'll find that quite a lot of things happen without the usual accompaniments.

The grin vanishes.

CUT TO:

EXT. MAD TEA PARTY - CONTINUOUS

A long table set beneath a tree, though only three places are in use. The MARCH HARE and the HATTER sit crammed together; the DORMOUSE sleeps between them.

HATTER
No room! No room!

ALICE
(sitting anyway)
There's plenty of room.

HATTER
(studying her)
Why is a raven like a writing-desk?

ALICE
I believe I can guess that.

MARCH HARE
Do you mean that you think you can find out the answer to it?

ALICE
Exactly so.

HATTER
Then you should say what you mean.

ALICE
I do -- at least I mean what I say -- that's the same thing, you know.

HATTER
Not the same thing a bit! You might just as well say that "I see what I eat" is the same thing as "I eat what I see."

The Dormouse stirs, mutters something about a treacle well, and falls back asleep mid-sentence.

Alice rises, exasperated.

ALICE
This is the stupidest tea party I ever was at in all my life.

She marches off. Behind her, the Hatter and Hare try to stuff the Dormouse into the teapot.

CUT TO:

EXT. QUEEN'S CROQUET GROUND - LATER

Playing-card GARDENERS paint white roses red in a panic. The QUEEN OF HEARTS approaches, flanked by cards bearing clubs.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(to the gardeners, thunderous)
Who has been painting my roses red?

TWO OF SPADES
(trembling)
May it please your Majesty, we were trying --

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Off with their heads!

Alice steps forward, unafraid.

ALICE
Nonsense. You're nothing but a pack of cards.

The Queen turns, incandescent with fury.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(shrieking)
Off with HER head!

The cards rise into the air, swirling around Alice like a startled flock.

CUT TO:

EXT. RIVERBANK - DAY (MATCH CUT)

Alice's eyes flutter open. She's back on the bank, head in her sister's lap, dry leaves drifting down instead of playing cards.

SISTER
Wake up, Alice dear! Why, what a long sleep you've had!

ALICE
(sitting up, dazed)
Oh, I've had such a curious dream --

She trails off, looking down the hedge row -- just for a moment, imagining she sees a flash of white.

FADE OUT.

> THE END <
